					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">psycopathicteen wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I find it a step backwards that Nintendo didn't connect the Super PPU to the cartridge like they did with the NES.  There's no expandability!</div>
<br />
<br />This would have meant at least 34 additional pins to the cartridge connector. The chosen way to update graphics on the SNES was obviously flexible DMA, instead of static CHR bankswitching schemes. Super FX cartridges demonstrated quite efficiently how the architecture could be expanded externally this way (the DMA bus is available on the cartridge slot).
<br />
<br />Makes perfect sense from a 1989/90 perspective.</div>

					
